  {
    "topic": "Tiger Reserves FAQ",
    "subtopics": [
      {
        "subtopic": "FAQs",
        "content": "• Q: What is a Tiger Reserve?\nA: A Tiger Reserve is a protected area dedicated to the conservation of tigers and their habitat. It includes a core area (minimal human activity) and a buffer area (with limited human interaction).\n\n• Q: Which is the 1st Tiger Reserve in India?\nA: Bandipur National Park in Karnataka, established in 1973-74.\n\n• Q: Which is the Largest Tiger Reserve in India?\nA: Nagarjunsagar-Srisailam, covering 3296.31 sq km.\n\n• Q: Which is the 53rd Tiger Reserve in India?\nA: Ranipur Tiger Reserve, Uttar Pradesh.\n\n• Q: How many Tiger Reserves are there in India?\nA: 57 tiger reserves as of December 3, 2024.\n\n• Q: Which Tiger Reserve has the highest tiger population?\nA: Corbett Tiger Reserve in Uttarakhand, with about 260 tigers (2022 Census).\n\n• Q: Which are some well-known Tiger Reserves in India?\nA: Jim Corbett (Uttarakhand), Ranthambore (Rajasthan), Bandhavgarh, Kanha, Pench (Madhya Pradesh), Sundarbans (West Bengal), Bandipur, Nagarhole (Karnataka), Periyar (Kerala).\n\n• Q: How does the government support Tiger Reserves?\nA: Through Project Tiger, NTCA funding, eco-development programs, and tiger population monitoring.\n\n• Q: What is the current tiger population in India?\nA: 3,167 tigers as per the 2022 Tiger Census (over 75% of the global population)."
      }
    ]
